docs.lead_paragraph: The Wild Rose was a much beloved and decrepit nightclub in Bridgehampton, N.Y., where patrons danced to live music, imbibed too much beer, and attained happiness and/or illness and/or pregnancy. It had been an entertainment establishment for almost a hundred years: Will Rogers twirled his lasso there in the '20s; politicians were caught with their lassos exposed in the '40s; and all manner of bands played one-night stands at the Wild Rose so they could bunk upstairs for a long weekend in the chichi Hamptons.

docs.lead_paragraph: T.R. Reid was a bureau chief in Tokyo and London for The Washington Post. His new book, "The Healing of America: A Global Quest for Better, Cheaper, and Fairer Health Care," is a systematic study of the health systems in seven countries that was inspired in part by his family's experiences living overseas and receiving health care abroad. Mr. Reid also produced a 2008 documentary on the same topic for PBS called "Sick Around the World." He spoke with blog contributor Anne Underwood.
